<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-798-164  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 798 164.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computers in Healthcare  Sept 1990 v11 n9 p36(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>LIS trends boost lab management efforts. (laboratory informationsystems) (Laboratory Special Edition)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rosen, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>New laboratory information systems (LIS) software combinescomputer technology with a random-access structure that providesthe flexibility and expandability of database management systemsinstead of the limited capacity of traditional flat file dataorganization.andP;  Data is stored in files that are less rigidlyrelated to each other and is managed by using menu-driven indexes.andO;One such LIS is 3M's Pathlab III System, which allows the user todefine the necessary information and format.andP;  Since users haveaccess to all items of data, using these new LIS packagesinevitably cause a laboratory's productivity to increase.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data Base Management SystemsInformation Storage and RetrievalApplicationsMedical LaboratoriesFile OrganizationSoftware Packages.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>